1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,980
 PRAZIOLA: Thank you very much, Boris. A very good morning to everyone. I want to thank Prime Minister Plankovic for being here this morning and start by congratulating you, the National Bank, Ministry of Finance and everybody in Croatia for the adoption of the euro on January 1st this year.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:32,000
 PRAZIOLA: Okay, bravo.

3
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:58,000
 It is a great pleasure to finally come to Dubrovnik. I have been aspiring for it for some time. I have a huge admiration for this incredibly successful, in its times, city.

4
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:04,000
 PRAZIOLA: And this admiration predates Game of Thrones.

5
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:15,000
 PRAZIOLA: In my comments, I would echo a bit what Boris was saying. It is really appropriate we are here.

6
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:21,000
 PRAZIOLA: This is a place that for centuries provided refuge

7
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:23,000
 PRAZIOLA: To ships

8
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,000
 PRAZIOLA: Wrestling with

9
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:28,000
 PRAZIOLA: Bad weather and choppy waters.

10
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:31,000
 PRAZIOLA: And that is what we are faced with today.

11
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:37,000
 PRAZIOLA: We have seen over the last years as Boris reminded us

12
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:51,000
 PRAZIOLA: Unthinkable events. The pandemic, the war and the very sudden increase in inflation rates

13
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:57,000
 PRAZIOLA: Leading to inevitably tightening of financial conditions.

14
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:05,000
 PRAZIOLA: I remember starting in my position in 2019 October, what did we talk about?

15
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:07,000
 PRAZIOLA: Low for longer.

16
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:09,000
 PRAZIOLA: Here we are now

17
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:11,000
 PRAZIOLA: Talking about

18
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:13,000
 PRAZIOLA: Higher for longer.

19
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:15,000
 PRAZIOLA: And that tremendous

20
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:17,000
 PRAZIOLA: Shifts

21
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:19,000
 PRAZIOLA: They tell us

22
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:21,000
 PRAZIOLA: A very important

23
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:23,000
 PRAZIOLA: Message

24
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:25,000
 PRAZIOLA: And Boris

25
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:27,000
 PRAZIOLA: Reflected on it.

26
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:29,000
 PRAZIOLA: We do have to learn to think of the unthinkable.

27
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:34,000
 PRAZIOLA: As policymakers we have to be much more adaptable than we used to be.

28
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:40,000
 PRAZIOLA: And this conference is going to help us to think together about agility, adaptability

29
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:43,000
 PRAZIOLA: In a more fragmented world.

30
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:46,000
 PRAZIOLA: So where is the region?

31
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 PRAZIOLA: Like the rest of the world, it is being hit by persistently high inflation

32
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,000
 PRAZIOLA: And slower growth.

33
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:01,000
 PRAZIOLA: We know that headline inflation has started going down not fast enough.

34
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:03,000
 PRAZIOLA: We are far from where we should be.

35
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:06,000
 PRAZIOLA: And core inflation is incredibly stubborn.

36
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:15,000
 PRAZIOLA: We project that inflation will stay well above central bank targets past 2024.

37
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:19,000
 PRAZIOLA: When we look into growth,

38
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:26,000
 PRAZIOLA: Let's remember that what has hit us is not without consequences.

39
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:38,000
 PRAZIOLA: We calculated that the loss for this region, central, eastern, south, eastern Europe,

40
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:45,000
 PRAZIOLA: For the five years since the pandemic is 3.5% of our GDP.

41
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:51,000
 PRAZIOLA: This is an equivalent of 50 billion euros wiped out.

42
00:03:51,000 --> 00:04:04,000
 PRAZIOLA: When we look into the key priorities for the times ahead, I want to concentrate on three.

43
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:13,000
 PRAZIOLA: First, on inflation and how you fight it without undermining your prospects for growth.

44
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:17,000
 PRAZIOLA: Very difficult set of choices.

45
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:20,000
 PRAZIOLA: Second, energy transition.

46
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:25,000
 PRAZIOLA: And third, how do you navigate a new era of fragmentation.

47
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:34,000
 PRAZIOLA: And like Boris, I would make references to Ragusa because it is actually remarkable how many we can make.

48
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:38,000
 PRAZIOLA: So let me start with bringing down inflation.

49
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:49,000
 PRAZIOLA: No one in this room by now doubts that the only way to win is to bring monetary policy,

50
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:55,000
 fiscal policy and structural reforms to work in sync.

51
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:04,000
 PRAZIOLA: And Ragusa tells us something about it, which is prudent fiscal policies, if I may use this term.

52
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:18,000
 PRAZIOLA: What I learned is that not only fiscal policy was effective, but it was also targeted to the most vulnerable people.

53
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:26,000
 PRAZIOLA: And I think we have to do the same in the new world we are faced with.

54
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:34,000
 PRAZIOLA: As unpleasant this is, I need to repeat what we have been saying for quite some time.

55
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:39,000
 PRAZIOLA: Fiscal consolidation has to speed up, exactly for the reason Boris elaborated.

56
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:41,000
 PRAZIOLA: I'm not going to repeat it.

57
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:47,000
 PRAZIOLA: What I want to add is that at the same time, we have to do the same in the new world we are faced with.

58
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:51,000
 PRAZIOLA: We have to double and triple efforts around structural reforms.

59
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 PRAZIOLA: Because otherwise we are going to be in slow growth for a long time.

60
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:59,000
 PRAZIOLA: I would add one more lesson we learned during the pandemic.

61
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:07,000
 PRAZIOLA: The same way people with strong immune systems withstood the virus.

62
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:13,000
 PRAZIOLA: Economies with strong fundamentals withstood the shock from the pandemic.

63
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:23,000
 PRAZIOLA: And that relentless pursuit of strong fundamentals investing in what would make countries of this region more competitive.

64
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:33,000
 PRAZIOLA: Reskilling, upskilling, making it so that we can grab every opportunity because we are well set, well prepared for it.

65
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:35,000
 PRAZIOLA: Subsidizing childcare.

66
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:48,000
 PRAZIOLA: If we want our labor market to be a little less problematic, we have to get every willing and able body to be able to join the labor market.

67
00:06:48,000 --> 00:07:01,000
 PRAZIOLA: And that actually applies also to our friends from Ukraine, those who had to leave their homes and come to other countries to escape the horror of the war.

68
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:13,000
 PRAZIOLA: Getting people to work is not only great for them and their future, it is great for the tight labor markets in many of our countries.

69
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:22,000
 PRAZIOLA: And I want to pay tribute to Poland and Estonia, creating online tools to help Ukrainians find jobs.

70
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:31,000
 PRAZIOLA: To the Czech Republic for addressing underemployment by making it easier to recognize refugees qualifications.

71
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 PRAZIOLA: And to everybody in the region for helping on the language front so refugees, Ukrainian refugees can work.

72
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:44,000
 PRAZIOLA: The Vice Governor of the Ukrainian Central Bank is somewhere here.

73
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:46,000
 PRAZIOLA: I'm looking at the audience.

74
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:49,000
 PRAZIOLA: Here it is.

75
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:53,000
 PRAZIOLA: I think we have a message to him and to the people of Ukraine.

76
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:55,000
 PRAZIOLA: We are with you.

77
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 PRAZIOLA: And we know you will be victorious.

78
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:11,000
 PRAZIOLA: I want to move to the second challenge, the energy security in this region.

79
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 PRAZIOLA: Look, what we have lived through with the shock of withdrawing from Russian oil and gas has been incredibly tough.

80
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:23,000
 PRAZIOLA: But also successful.

81
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:33,000
 PRAZIOLA: I think that even Europeans, me being one of them, we did not expect at the start of this withdrawal

82
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:46,000
 PRAZIOLA: That we will be so successful that actually our economies will come true with a more or less positive growth in this year.

83
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:49,000
 PRAZIOLA: But let's not kid ourselves.

84
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:52,000
 PRAZIOLA: The job is so far from being done.

85
00:08:52,000 --> 00:09:01,000
 PRAZIOLA: There is so much more that needs to be pursued in this region for energy efficiency, for renewables

86
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:11,000
 PRAZIOLA: and for changing consumer and investment patterns to low carbon climate resilient growth.

87
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:20,000
 PRAZIOLA: I am a big advocate of using carbon price as an incentive, predictable, so business knows where it is going to go.

88
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:24,000
 PRAZIOLA: I know that not everybody is yet sought on this.

89
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:36,000
 PRAZIOLA: Boys and girls, ladies and gentlemen, we have to move because if we don't, the implications for our competitiveness

90
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:43,000
 PRAZIOLA: and for the sustainability of growth are going to be very significant.

91
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,000
 PRAZIOLA: Again, Ragusa, interesting example.

92
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 PRAZIOLA: They didn't have to deal with energy.

93
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:51,000
 PRAZIOLA: They didn't have to deal with Russian oil and gas.

94
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:54,000
 PRAZIOLA: But they had to deal with water.

95
00:09:54,000 --> 00:10:01,000
 PRAZIOLA: So they built an aqueduct 12 kilometers long in these days to secure water supply.

96
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:11,000
 PRAZIOLA: If they could do it in these days, we sure can build the infrastructure that makes our economies strong and resilient.

97
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:18,000
 PRAZIOLA: I am going to move to the third challenge, navigating a fragmented world.

98
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:20,000
 PRAZIOLA: Let's face it.

99
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:23,000
 PRAZIOLA: We are in a very tough place.

100
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:30,000
 PRAZIOLA: Our countries and the world as a whole has enjoyed something remarkable: peace dividend.

101
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:40,000
 PRAZIOLA: Since the end of the Cold War, Russia's invasion destroyed that peace dividend.

102
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:50,000
 PRAZIOLA: Understandably, countries now have to pay much more attention to defense because we cannot anymore take peace in Europe for granted.

103
00:10:50,000 --> 00:11:02,000
 PRAZIOLA: But that means that we are going to be constrained because there is opportunity cost of what we spend on defense vis-à-vis what we spend on anything else.

104
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:14,000
 PRAZIOLA: On top of it, we have a more fragmented world that this war just accelerated in a direction that is particularly damaging for emerging market economies.

105
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:24,000
 PRAZIOLA: Let's remember, over the last decades, the world economy tripled on the grounds of integration.

106
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:28,000
 PRAZIOLA: Who was the biggest beneficiary? Emerging markets.

107
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:32,000
 PRAZIOLA: They quadrupled at that time.

108
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 PRAZIOLA: But rich countries also benefited. They doubled.

109
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:41,000
 PRAZIOLA: Now we are looking into a future where, based on our assessments, the cost of fragmentation,

110
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:48,000
 PRAZIOLA: if we run it badly, can be devastating.

111
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:59,000
 PRAZIOLA: We have a range just from trade fragmentation, a range between 0.2% of GDP loss and 7% loss.

112
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:08,000
 PRAZIOLA: 7% is an equivalent of taking Japan and Germany and wiping them out from the world economy.

113
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:14,000
 PRAZIOLA: Who is going to bear the consequences? It would be mostly emerging markets.

114
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:18,000
 PRAZIOLA: Now, we can think of fragmentation only as evil.

115
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:22,000
 PRAZIOLA: We also can say, hey, there are opportunities.

116
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:25,000
 PRAZIOLA: Opportunities if we are more competitive, to be more attractive.

117
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:33,000
 PRAZIOLA: Opportunities because of moving supply chains closer to home, possibly away from Asia.

118
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:38,000
 PRAZIOLA: And opportunities for us integrating our economies more.

119
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:44,000
 PRAZIOLA: Something that, by the way, we have a long, long, long mile to go.

120
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:52,000
 PRAZIOLA: I want to finish by saying in this world of more uncertainty, more challenges,

121
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:59,000
 PRAZIOLA: even more it is important for our family, the IMF family, to be strong together.

122
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:07,000
 PRAZIOLA: Just three days ago, at our Board of Directors, we discussed increasing the family

123
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:13,000
 PRAZIOLA: by having yet another European country, Liechtenstein, potentially joining.

124
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:16,000
 PRAZIOLA: So going to 191.

125
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:29,000
 PRAZIOLA: What we offer is one, the value of keeping a hand on the pulse of each and every economy

126
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:37,000
 PRAZIOLA: and giving you a perspective that individually, even the EU as a whole, cannot possibly have.

127
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:44,000
 PRAZIOLA: And we intend to perform this function thoroughly in the years to come.

128
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:48,000
 PRAZIOLA: Secondly, we offer policy coordination.

129
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:54,000
 PRAZIOLA: Boris was right to say in the spring of 2020, we were scared.

130
00:13:54,000 --> 00:14:00,000
 PRAZIOLA: We were predicting the world economy to contract by around 10 percent.

131
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:02,000
 PRAZIOLA: It did contract 3.1.

132
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:05,000
 PRAZIOLA: Why did contract so little?

133
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:10,000
 PRAZIOLA: Because of policy coordination, monetary policy coordination, fiscal policy coordination.

134
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:17,000
 PRAZIOLA: And we, the Fund, we believe that we have a huge responsibility to carry that forward.

135
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:21,000
 PRAZIOLA: And last but not least, of course, by providing financing to those who need it.

136
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:27,000
 PRAZIOLA: During these last years, we have funded over 300 billion.

137
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:32,000
 PRAZIOLA: Largest, largest commitment to 96 countries.

138
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:36,000
 PRAZIOLA: Never in our history we have done so much for so many.

139
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:40,000
 PRAZIOLA: And, of course, we did the SDR allocation.

140
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 PRAZIOLA: Here in this region, we are financing Kosovo, Moldova, Serbia, North Macedonia, and, of course, Ukraine.

141
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:52,000
 PRAZIOLA: And I want to bring, since I have to finish with something you don't know.

142
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:59,000
 PRAZIOLA: We now have the first Resilience and Sustainability Trust program for this region.

143
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:01,000
 PRAZIOLA: It is for Kosovo.

144
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:04,000
 PRAZIOLA: And we hope there would be many more to come.

145
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:08,000
 PRAZIOLA: I want to finish with a reference to last night, Boris.

146
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:13,000
 PRAZIOLA: We were in Lazareti.

147
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:16,000
 PRAZIOLA: What does that present?

148
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:20,000
 PRAZIOLA: Think long term and built to last.

149
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:28,000
 PRAZIOLA: So may we do that in our beautiful, vibrant, resilient, strong region.

150
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:30,000
 PRAZIOLA: Thank you very much.

151
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:32,000
 PRAZIOLA:

152
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:33,000
 PRAZIOLA:

